orence, Boccaccio develops in these stories of jests a self-consciously literary representation of the Florentine social imaginary. The essays in this volume, all written by prominent scholars, survey previous scholarship and open up new cultural and historical perspectives on Boccaccio’s sophisticated art of storytelling. They analyze both the literary sources that Boccaccio’s comic narratives transform, as well as the political, legal, and ethical contexts with which they engage. Each contributor tackles a single tale, yet their essays also register major themes and concerns that recur throughout Day Eight, allowing for close connections among the essays.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / Italian.2bisacsh  aCommedia.  aDante.  aDecameron Eighth Day.  aDecameron.  aFlorence.  aGiovanni Boccaccio.  aMedieval Italy.  ahistory of pranks.  amedieval literature.  anarrative.  anovella.  apractical jokes.  ashort story.  astorytelling.1 aBarolini, Teodolinda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrilli, Elisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Katherine A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClarke, K.P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDaniels, Rhiannon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFaibisoff, Leah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFritz-Morkin, Maggie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHolmes, Olivia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMorosini, Roberta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRobins, William , eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/rel